  "prompt": "How is Josh Elliott doing at NBC Sports? Was it a smart move for him to leave Good Morning America?",
  "response": "As of the latest updates, Josh Elliott has been with NBC Sports since leaving **Good Morning America (GMA)** in 2014. His departure from GMA was notable because he was a key member of the morning show, which was highly successful at the time. However, his transition to NBC Sports has been somewhat low-key compared to his time on morning television.\n\nIt\u2019s difficult to definitively assess whether leaving GMA was a \"smart move\" for Elliott, as it depends on his personal and professional goals. Here are some points to consider:\n\n### Pros of the Move to NBC Sports:\n1. **Diverse Opportunities**: At NBC Sports, Elliott has had the chance to work on a variety of sports coverage, including the Olympics, Notre Dame football, and horse racing events like the Kentucky Derby.\n2. **Less Visibility, Less Pressure**: Moving from the high-profile, high-pressure world of morning TV to sports broadcasting might have allowed him to focus on his passion for sports without the intense public scrutiny.\n3. **Longevity in Sports**: Sports broadcasting often has a longer career trajectory compared to morning TV, which can be more age-sensitive.\n\n### Cons of the Move:\n1. **Lower Profile**: While GMA made him a household name, his role at NBC Sports has not garnered the same level of attention or fame.\n2. **Missed Opportunities on Live TV**: Some critics argue that Elliott\u2019s charisma and talent were better suited for live, personality-driven shows like GMA rather than sports coverage.\n3. **Less Career Momentum**: His transition has not led to the same level of career advancement or recognition as his time on GMA.\n\nUltimately, Elliott\u2019s move to NBC Sports may have been a personal choice driven by lifestyle preferences or a desire to focus on sports journalism. While it hasn\u2019t propelled him to the same level of public visibility as his time on GMA, it might align more closely with his passions and long-term goals. Whether it was a \"smart move\" is subjective and depends on what he values most in his career.",
